    <h1>Functors</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Bartosz Milewski · 2015 · <a href="https://bartoszmilewski.com/2015/01/20/functors/">Category Theory for Programmers, Ch. 7</a></p>

    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-6">Prereqs: <a href="/reading/category-theory/milewski-01/">🍞 Ch1</a> (Category), <a href="/reading/category-theory/milewski-02/">🍞 Ch2</a> (Types and Functions). 7 min.</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">A <strong>functor</strong> is a structure-preserving map between categories. It maps objects to objects and morphisms to morphisms, so that composition and identity are preserved: <code>fmap id = id</code> and <code>fmap (g . f) = fmap g . fmap f</code>. Every container type you already use &mdash; list, optional, function &mdash; is a functor. <code>fmap</code> is the operation that makes it one.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. What is a functor? -->
    <h3>What is a functor?</h3>
    <p>A functor maps one category to another. It sends each object to an object and each morphism to a morphism, preserving the wiring: if <code>h = g . f</code> in the source category, then <code>F(h) = F(g) . F(f)</code> in the target. In programming, both categories are the same (types and functions), so a functor is a type constructor plus an <code>fmap</code> that lifts functions inside the container. Functors also show up in unexpected places: <a href="https://june.kim/licenses-are-functors"><img src="/reading/jk.png" alt="jk" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>software licenses are functors</a> from a derivation category to an obligations category, preserving the composition of derivative works.</p>

